T1  - Deregulation and oligopolistic rivalry in bank deposit markets
AU  - VanHoose, David D.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 12
IS  - 3
SP  - 379
EP  - 388
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(88)90004-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426688900040
AB  - This paper provides a partial equilibrium analysis of a deregulated market for bank deposits in which banks behave oligopolistically but entry and exit are freely permitted. It is demonstrated that the effects of variations in market interest rates, reserve requirements, and bank cost and demand conditions upon the market quantity of bank deposit money are fundamentally altered if the degree of bank rivalry adjusts endogenously. Hence, banking deregulation may produce significant changes in the relationships between these variables and the stock of deposit money.
ER  - 
